# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1935-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1935-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1935-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1935-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1935-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1935-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1935-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1935-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1935-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1935-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1935-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1935-world-series/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1935-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1935-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1935-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1935-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1935-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1935-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1935-world-series/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1878 Chicago White Stockings season** was the seventh season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third in the National League and the first at Lakefront Park.
[src:1935-world-series/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fourth in the National League with a record of 30–30.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The **1935 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1935 season.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The 32nd edition of the World Series, it matched the Detroit Tigers and the Chicago Cubs.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The Tigers won in six games for their first championship in five Series appearances, as they had lost in 1907, 1908, 1909, and 1934.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] This was the first championship ever won by a Detroit-based team.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The Tigers won despite losing the services of first baseman Hank Greenberg.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] In Game 2, Greenberg collided with Cubs catcher Gabby Hartnett and broke his wrist, sidelining him for the rest of the Series.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The Cubs had won 21 consecutive games in September (still a record as of 2021), eventually taking the National League pennant by four games over the defending World Series champions, the St.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] In Game 6, Tommy Bridges pitched a complete-game victory to win the Series for Detroit.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] With the score tied 3–3 in the top of the ninth inning, Bridges gave up a leadoff triple to Stan Hack, but retired the next three batters without the runner on third scoring.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] In the bottom of the ninth, Goose Goslin drove in the winning run with two outs.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] After the game, manager Mickey Cochrane said the following of Bridges' gutsy performance: "A hundred and fifty pounds of courage.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] In addition to Bridges, the Tigers had a hitting hero.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Right fielder Pete Fox accumulated ten hits and an average of .385 for the Series.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Detroit owner Frank Navin, then 64 years old, had been running the organization for 30 years and had seen four of his teams win American League pennants, only to lose four World Series.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Six weeks after the Tigers finally won the World Series in October 1935, Navin suffered a heart attack while riding a horse and died.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] A pitching duel between Lon Warneke and Schoolboy Rowe, both of whom went the distance, was decided by its leadoff batter, Augie Galan, doubling, and scoring on an error by Rowe that allowed Billy Herman to reach and eventually score on a Gabby Hartnett single.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Frank Demaree added a homer in the ninth inning for the visiting Cubs.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] In the bottom of the first, Jo-Jo White hit a leadoff single and scored on a double by Mickey Cochrane, who scored on Charlie Gehringer's single before Hank Greenberg's two-run home run knocked Cubs' starter Charlie Root out of the game.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] In the fourth, Roy Henshaw got two outs before letting the Tigers load the bases on a single, hit-by-pitch and walk.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] A wild pitch scored a run, then after a walk reloaded the bases, Gehringer's two-run single made it 7–0 Tigers.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The Cubs got on the board in the fifth when Phil Cavarretta reached first on an error, moved to second on a groundout and scored on Billy Jurges's single.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The Cubs got two more runs in the seventh on Billy Herman's single with runners on second and third, but the Tigers added a run in the bottom half on Pete Fox's RBI single off Fabian Kowalik.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Tommy Bridges pitched a complete game as the Tigers' 8–3 tied the series heading to Chicago.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] In Game 3, Frank Demaree's leadoff home run in the second off Elden Auker put Chicago on the board.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] A one-out single and subsequent error put runners on first and third before Bill Lee's ground out made it 2–0 Cubs.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] They added a run in the fifth when Billy Jurges drew a leadoff walk, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt and scored on Augie Galan's single.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The Tigers got on the board in the sixth when Goose Goslin singled off Lee and scored on Pete Fox's triple.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] In the eighth, after a walk and double, Goslin's two-run single tied the game and knocked Lee out.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Reliever Lon Warneke allowed two singles, the second of which to Billy Rogell scoring a run, then Fox stole home to make it 5–3 Tigers.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Detroit brought back Game 1 starter Schoolboy Rowe in relief.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] He allowed three straight one-out singles in the ninth, the last of which to Ken O'Dea, before Augie Galan's sacrifice fly sent the game into extra innings, but Rowe nailed down the victory after Jo-Jo White's RBI single scored the winning run off Larry French in the 11th.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] This game remarkably featured four ejections.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The Tigers lost coach Del Baker while The Cubs lost Woody English, Tuck Stainback and manager Charlie Grimm.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Neither English nor Stainback were in the game.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Chicago threatened against Crowder with a pair of one-out hits in the ninth, but Stan Hack grounded into a game-ending 6-4-3 double play.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Staving off elimination, the Cubs got a two-run home run from Chuck Klein after a leadoff triple in the second.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] They added another run in the seventh on Billy Herman's RBI double off Schoolboy Rowe.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] They replaced Lon Warneke after six innings with right-hander Bill Lee, who gave up Detroit's only run in the ninth on three consecutive singles (the last of which to Pete Fox before settling down to retire the final three batters.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] This was the first of three World Series games that the Cubs have won in Wrigley Field (where they had previously lost 6 Series games).
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The other wins were Game 6 in 1945, and Game 5 in 2016.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] In Game 6, Pete Fox's RBI double off Larry French put the Tigers on the board.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Billy Herman's RBI single tied the game in the third off Tommy Bridges, who put the Tigers back in front in the fourth with an RBI groundout with two on, but Herman's two-run home run in the fifth put the Cubs ahead 3–2.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The Tigers tied the game in the sixth when Billy Rogell doubled with two outs and scored on Marv Owen's single.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] Stan Hack tripled to lead off the top of the ninth for the Cubs, but was left stranded at third.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] In the bottom of the ninth, Mickey Cochrane singled and moved to second on a groundout before Goose Goslin's walk-off single won it in front of Detroit's home fans, pitcher Tommy Bridges getting his second win of the Series.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] When the Detroit Tigers won the 1935 World Series, the city of Detroit was mired in the Great Depression, which had hit the city and its industries particularly hard.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] With the Stanley Cup win, the city had seen three major league championships in less than a year.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The Tigers would return to the World Series in 1940 World Series, but they would narrowly fall to the Cincinnati Reds in seven games after being nine outs away from the championship in Game 7, which would be the last time the Tigers lost in the World Series until 2006.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The Tigers would win their next title in 1945 in a rematch against the Cubs in seven games.
[src:1935-world-series/1935-world-series] The Cubs returned to the World Series in 1938, but were swept by the New York Yankees, becoming the third victim of a Yankees four-peat from 1936 to 1939.
